## Proposal:

```
namespace System.IO
{
    public class File
    {
        public static bool TryDelete(string path);
        public static bool TryDelete(string path, int numberOfRetries = 0, int timeout = 250);
    }
}
```
## Background

A very common problem is that when trying to delete a file it's used by another process which raises an exception. A very common solution is that File.Delete is wrapped around with a try-catch, possibly wrapped around a loop retrying for a specific amount of times. As no developer knows exactly what happens outside of his code, a File.Delete is probably always wrapped with a try-catch. 

With this proposal I would like to reduce the amount of lines and give this away to .NET to take care of.

## Reason

TryDelete tries to delete a file for a specific amount of times which reduces the amount of code developers write every day since File.Delete is likely always a "Try to delete and do X if it fails" in code anyway by being surrounded with a try-catch. Having the option to retry is an additional line of code saver but not explicitly necessary.

It behaves similar to Dictionary.TryGetValue for example which only purpose is is to save a few lines as well.

## Proposal:

```
namespace System.IO
{
    public class File
    {
        public static bool Delete(string path);
        public static bool Delete(string path, FileDeletion mode = FileDeletion.Permanent);

        public enum FileDeletion
        {
            ///<summary>Permanently deletes a file</summary>
            Permanent,
            ///<summary>Deletes a file to recycle bin if possible. Otherwise falls back to permanently deletion</summary>
            RecycleBin
        }

    }
}
```
## Reason

As of now, no managed API exists to delete a file by moving it into the recycle bin. VB.NET have this option by using FileSystem.DeleteFile. C# however would require to use unmanaged API SHFileOperation in shell32 or referencing VB.NET library, in Windows at least.

This proposed API might be useful in cases where the customer decides to delete a file himself in a software. We could move it to recycle bin which give them the opportunity to restore if necessary, which is a top requested feature for any software that allows that.

A recycle bin is available in Windows and MacOS, not sure about Linux although Ubuntu have a trash if I remember correctly. There must be a simply fallback to delete a file permanently if moving to recycle bin is not possible. This is also the case for deleting files from a network storage or attachable drive so it has to be documented anyway and should be clear to all developers. This makes the API available on all platforms.

Proposal:

```csharp
namespace System.Security.Cryptography {
  public struct HashAlgorithmName {
    public static HashAlgorithmName FromOid(Oid oid);
    public static HashAlgorithmName FromOid(string oidValue);
  }
}
```

Rationale:

I write this  _a lot_.

```csharp
switch (DigestAlgorithm.Value) {
  case KnownOids.MD5:
    return HashAlgorithmName.MD5;
  case KnownOids.SHA1:
    return HashAlgorithmName.SHA1;
  case KnownOids.SHA256:
    return HashAlgorithmName.SHA256;
  case KnownOids.SHA384:
    return HashAlgorithmName.SHA384;
  case KnownOids.SHA512:
    return HashAlgorithmName.SHA512;
  default:
    throw new CryptographicException();
}
```

Such examples would be when a `HashAlgorithmName` is needed to pass in to `Verify` or `Sign` of RSA / ECDsa, etc.

The `string` overload would be useful because in most circumstances I don't have an actual `Oid` instance. It's easy enough to construct one, but the actual implementation doesn't need one - it's going to want the string representation anyway. It felt silly require constructing an `Oid` object just to shuffle a string around. Perhaps then the `Oid` overload is not necessary.

Other thoughts:

* Should the `string` parameter be a `ReadOnlySpan<char>` instead?

* Should there be "Try" versions of this to return false if it fails to map an OID to a `HashAlgorithm` and the value is an `out`?

